The paper deals with computational complexity of manipulative actions in elections, which falls under the category of computational game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses algorithms and election systems, which are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data structures (cs.DS). The study of complexity of manipulative actions also involves analysis of algorithms and machine learning, which are relevant to learning theory (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with the complexity of algorithms, which is relevant to computational complexity (cs.CC).
